Implement the private `safe_call/1` function. It takes a zero-arity `fetch_fn`
and must normalise any outcome into a tagged `{:ok, _} | {:error, _}` tuple so
that a fetch can never crash the caller.

Call `fetch_fn.()` and inspect its return value:

- If it returns `{:ok, value}`, return that `{:ok, value}` tuple unchanged.
- If it returns `{:error, reason}`, return that `{:error, reason}` tuple unchanged.
- For any other return value `other`, return `{:error, {:unexpected_return, other}}`.

The call must also be fully guarded against non-local exits:

- If `fetch_fn.()` raises an exception, rescue it and return `{:error, exception}`.
- If it throws or exits, catch the `kind` and `value` and return `{:error, {kind, value}}`.

In every case the function returns a tuple; it never propagates the failure.

